{"title": "American Language", "description": "\"It was part of my daily work, for a good many years, to read the principal English newspapers and reviews; it has been part of my work, all the time, to read the more important English novels, essays, poetry and criticism. An American born and bred, I early noted, as everyone else in like case must note, certain salient differences between the English of England and the English of America as practically spoken and written\u2014differences in vocabulary, in syntax, in the shades and habits of idiom, and even, coming to the common speech, in grammar. And I noted too, of course, partly during visits to England but more largely by a somewhat wide and intimate intercourse with English people in the United States, the obvious differences between English and American pronunciation and intonation.\n Greatly interested in these differences\u2014some of them so great that they led me to seek exchanges of light with Englishmen\u2014I looked for some work that would describe and account for them with a show of completeness, and perhaps depict the process of their origin. I soon found that no such work existed, either in England or in America\u2014that the whole literature of the subject was astonishingly meagre and unsatisfactory.\" - Summary by Mencken (Preface)", "duration": 56474, "language": "English", "authors": [{"id": "637", "name": "H. L. Mencken"}], "coverArt": "https://archive.org/download/americanlanguage_1801_librivox/americanlanguage_1801.jpg", "copyright_year": "1919", "genres": ["Literary Criticism", "Writing & Linguistics"], "supporters": [{"role": "Read by", "name": "LibriVox Volunteers"}, {"role": "Book Coordinator", "name": "DrPGould"}, {"role": "Meta Coordinator", "name": "Phil Chenevert"}, {"role": "Proof Listener", "name": "Barbara Baker"}], "sections": [{"section": 0, "title": "Preface", "readers": [11651], "path": "http://www.archive.org/download/americanlanguage_1801_librivox/americanlanguage_00_mencken_6